><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-introductory-tutorial/">Bodysuit with Corset Cups <span>(9)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="24"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-measurement/">Party Dress <span>(17)</span></a></li></ul></li><li class="active">					<a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/categories/#544">Transparent corsets  <span>(4)</span></a><ul class="list-unstyled"><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="25"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-getting-acquainted-with-the-model-cutting-a-mock-up/">Corset with Drapery <span>(20)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="26"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-getting-acquainted-with-the-model-and-the-throw-over-sewing-technique/">Corset with Integral Straps <span>(27)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="34"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-getting-acquainted-with-the-model/">Corset with 3-Part Cups <span>(22)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="76"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-getting-acquainted-with-the-model-5/">Corset with a Fancy Cut-Out <span>(22)</span></a></li></ul></li><li class="active">					<a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/categories/#3082">Decoration Techniques  <span>(9)</span></a><ul class="list-unstyled"><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="83"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-decoration-materials/">Rhinestones Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="84"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-glue-on-half-pearls/">Additional Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="85"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-thick-decoration-element/">Thick Decoration Elements <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="86"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-decoration-materials-2/">Wedding Dress Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="87"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-types-of-sequins/">Sequins Decoration <span>(11)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="105"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-marking-the-borders-of-the-decoration/">Casual Garment Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="106"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/epaulettes-function-and-materials/">Epaulettes <span>(8)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="127"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tambour-or-luneville-embroidery-part-1/">Tambour or Luneville Embroidery <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="128"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/the-button-loop-closure-part-1/">The Button Loop Closure <span>(2)</span></a></li></ul></li><li class="active">					<a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/categories/#4289">Fancy Dresses for Girls  <span>(5)</span></a><ul class="list-unstyled"><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="118"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/childrens-body-proportions/">The Law of Proportions in Children's Wear <span>(3)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="117"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-style-for-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 3 Years Old Girl <span>(9)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="119"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-dress/">Fancy Dress for 6 Years Old Girl <span>(16)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="120"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-style-with-respect-to-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 9 Years Old Girl <span>(14)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="135"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-dress-with-regard-to-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 12 Years Old Girl <span>(14)</span></a></li></ul></li>		</ul></div></div>													<div class="lesson-tab" role="tabpanel">				  <!-- Nav tabs -->				  <ul class="nav nav-tabs" role="tablist">					<li role="presentation" class="active"><a href="#about" aria-controls="about" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Course details</a></li>																		<li role="presentation"><a href="#transcript" aria-controls="transcript" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Transcript</a></li>														<li role="presentation"><a href="#pattern" aria-controls="pattern" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Pattern</a></li>					<li role="presentation"><a href="#diploma" aria-controls="transcript" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Diploma</a></li>						<li role="presentation"><a class="faq-tab blank" href="#faq" aria-controls="faq" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">FAQs</a></li>				  </ul>				  <!-- Tab panes -->				  <div class="tab-content">				  																									<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane active" id="about">											<div class="dark-get-started margin-0">																																											<p><strong>Dressmaker’s Treasury will equip you with a range of necessary tools and techniques which every professional must possess for successful work.</strong></p><p><strong>It will help you get more confident. You will know how to: </strong></p><ul><li>Choose the right strategy for making a garment after your first meeting with the client;</li><li>Take necessary measurements correctly and prepare and fill out an order form;</li><li>Choose the right basic pattern and adjust it after your client’s measurements with the help of automatic pattern adjustments calculation tables;</li><li>Avoid common mistakes which result in ill-fitting necklines by choosing the right sewing technique.</li></ul><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>The course&nbsp;is&nbsp;useful both to beginner dressmakers, as well as experienced professionals.</strong></p><p><strong>Author:</strong>&nbsp;Tatiana Kozorovitsky</p><p><strong>Total length:</strong>&nbsp;5h 16m</p>												</div>						</div>										<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane" id="transcript">						<div class="overlay"></div>						<!-- BEGIN Schema.org microdata added by the Add-Meta-Tags WordPress plugin --><!-- Scope BEGIN: Article --><div itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Article"><!-- Scope BEGIN: Organization --><span itemprop="publisher" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Organization"><meta itemprop="name" content="Corset Academy"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="logo" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="name" content="Corset Academy logo"><meta itemprop="text" content="Corset Academy logo"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="width" content="303"><meta itemprop="height" content="49"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/png"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/"><meta itemprop="sameAs" content="https://www.facebook.com/corsetacademy"></span> <!-- Scope END: Organization --><!-- Scope BEGIN: Person --><span itemprop="author" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Person"><meta itemprop="name" content="Tatiana Kozorovitsky"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="image" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/uploads/MVI_3285.MOV.00_00_31_09.Still001-128x128.jpg"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/uploads/MVI_3285.MOV.00_00_31_09.Still001-128x128.jpg"><meta itemprop="width" content="128"><meta itemprop="height" content="128"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/jpeg"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/author/infocorsetacademy-net/"><meta itemprop="sameAs" content="http://www.corsetacademy.net"></span> <!-- Scope END: Person --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-7-supplementary-measurements-for-sleeves-or-shoulder-straps/"><meta itemprop="mainEntityOfPage" content="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-7-supplementary-measurements-for-sleeves-or-shoulder-straps/"><meta itemprop="datePublished" content="2017-11-30T16:12:11+00:00"><meta itemprop="dateModified" content="2017-11-30T16:12:22+00:00"><meta itemprop="copyrightYear" content="2017"><meta itemprop="inLanguage" content="en_US"><meta itemprop="name" content="Tutorial 7. Supplementary Measurements for Sleeves or Shoulder Straps."><meta itemprop="headline" content="Tutorial 7. Supplementary Measurements for Sleeves or Shoulder Straps."><meta itemprop="description" content="In this tutorial, we will talk about measurements relevant for a corset which has some parts extending beyond. Sleeves, shoulder straps, halter straps"><meta itemprop="articleSection" content="Wedding and Evening Dresses. Theoretical Part."><meta itemprop="keywords" content="wedding and evening dresses. theoretical part., video"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="image" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="width" content="303"><meta itemprop="height" content="49"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/png"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><div itemprop="articleBody"><h1>Tutorial 7. Supplementary Measurements for Sleeves or Shoulder Straps.</h1><p><strong>In this tutorial, we will talk about measurements relevant for a corset which has some parts extending beyond its supposed top edge. </strong>It can be sleeves, shoulder straps, halter straps, etc.</p><p>We will touch upon the choice of patterns for such garments a little later.</p><p><strong>There is a whole range of additional measurements which must be taken very accurately in order to ensure a good fit of any shoulder part added to the corset. </strong></p><p>These measurements are also to be recorded in the order form.</p><p><strong>I start from the measurements related to the front and then take the ones related to the back. </strong></p><p><strong>Bust to Shoulder:</strong></p><p><strong>This measurement, also known as Bust Height, is the distance from the end point of Bust Princess Seam Width to the High Shoulder Point.</strong></p><p><strong>Please remember </strong>that this measurement is taken from the end point of Bust Princess Seam to Bust Princess Seam which is not the same as Bust Apex to Bust Apex.</p><p><strong>This is because </strong>the top part of the garment needs to be aligned with the corset it is sewn to, so all measurements for this top part need to be taken from the same reference points as for the corset.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%207.files/image002.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>Bust to Shoulder Tip: </strong></p><p><strong>It is the distance from the end point of Bust Princess Seam Width to the shoulder tip point. </strong></p><p><strong>This measurement allows you to determine your client’s front shoulder slope. </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%207.files/image004.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>Shoulder: </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%207.files/image006.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>Knowing these three measurements, you can build a triangle on the pattern with respect to your client’s shoulder slope. </strong>This triangle, transferred on the pattern, will really help you if your garment is supposed to have shoulder straps which may require some adjustments.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%207.files/image008.jpg" alt=""></p><p>Over-Bust Width Front<strong>:</strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%207.files/image010.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>Centre Length Front: </strong></p><p><strong>This measurement is taken as distance from centre waist point to centre front neck point. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%207.files/image012.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>Shoulder to Shoulder Across Front: </strong></p><p><strong>It is the distance from shoulder to shoulder taken with the measuring tape going across the front at the neck base level.</strong> I hold the measuring tape edgeways for this purpose.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%207.files/image014.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>Side Length: </strong></p><p><strong>If your garment features sleeves, then it is very important to determine the right side length before working on the sleeves themselves. </strong></p><p><strong>Conversations about corset garments with shoulder seams often start from the same question: </strong>“How to make the sleeves comfortable and, at the same time, make sure they won’t rip in the armpit area?”</p><p><strong>The answer lies in the length of the side seam. It should be as long as possible, </strong>i.e. reach to the very underarm and stop right at it.</p><p><strong>But there are also other factors you need to account for. </strong></p><p><strong>For example, if you want to make a corset with shoulder seams and sleeves,</strong> then you had better think it over how to join the sleeves correctly with the side seams, as well as the armscyes.</p><p><strong>Do not forget that the corset is rather thick. </strong>It is made of at least four layers: face fabric, lining, and two layers of woven interfacing. When the side seam stops right at the underarm, the thick seam allowance starts rubbing on it and irritating the skin. This is why you need to use special techniques to join the side seam with the sleeve of your corset: for example, step from the edge of your corset pieces when you are duplicating them so as to leave the side seam allowance soft and thin. Think about how you can fold the armscye seam allowance to prevent it from obstructing the wearer’s arm movements.</p><p><strong>In our case, the garment is made of a corset and a soft top with sleeves. It is technically a lot easier to construct sleeves and attach them to a soft top rather than to a corset. </strong></p><p><strong>Requirements to the side seam remain the same for a top like ours. </strong>It should reach right to the underarm. But in such garments the side seam is divided into two sections: the side seam of the corset (of the particular length you have determined) which blends in with the side seam of the soft top. This top part of the side seam needs to be added to the pattern of the top. And the armscye of the top should be rather narrow to stay comfortable in wear.</p><p><strong>Let me try to explain why the side seam needs to be so long in such corset-and-top garments. </strong>The thing is the corset has a tight fit in the waist and holds around it firmly.</p><p><strong>Please look at how a regular non-corset garment, such as a jacket, behaves when you raise your arm. </strong>The whole garment “follows” your arm. Of course, no one notices it in the everyday life. Your client doesn’t even think about how her jacket or blazer moves if she raises her arm. Nor does she think about it when she is wearing some kind of an elastic blouse or a turtle-neck top. The entire side seam simply stretches out together with the adjoining areas of fabric, or the whole garment moves up just a little.</p><p><strong>This is not our case because the corset “hugs” the waist firmly and we cannot and must not shift it. </strong>And this means there will be very much tension in the underarm area when the woman raises her arm. The sleeve will simply get ripped out unless we either provide for some kind of elastic stretchy inset in this area or ensure the largest possible armscye and the longest possible side length!</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%207.files/image016.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>I hope I have managed to explain what makes the right choice of side length so important. </strong></p><p><strong>You will need a whole set of other measurements to build the sleeve of your corset. </strong></p><p><strong>Armscye Circumference: </strong></p><p><strong>Armscye Circumference is measured by putting the measuring tape around the top of your client’s arm with the smallest possible armscye allowance. </strong>There is no freedom of movement allowance for corset armscyes and sleeves.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%207.files/image018.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>I want to share a good trick with you which will help you ensure a good fit of the sleeve.</strong> You can slightly increase the shoulder length, i.e. slightly lower the armscye. Although this won’t make a huge difference, the wearer will still feel more comfortable moving her arms.</p><p><strong>Arm Fullness: </strong></p><p><strong>This measurement is very important considering that we are making tight-fit sleeves. It is taken in the area where the arm joins the shoulder. </strong>The client should keep her arm hanging down.</p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%207.files/image020.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%207.files/image022.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>There is an important detail you need to know when measuring Arm Fullness. </strong></p><p>If you know that your fabric will not stretch very well, then <strong>it makes sense to take another Arm Fullness measurement after asking your client to put her hand on her hip. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%207.files/image024.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>You should be able to determine how much the fabric needs to stretch after comparing the two resulting measurements. </strong></p><p><strong>In other words, you will know how far the sleeve should be able to stretch to be comfortable in wear. </strong></p><p><strong>If the fabric you have chosen cannot stretch that well </strong>(i.e. corresponding with the difference between the two measurements), then you should either change the style of the top or change the fabric after discussing it with the client.</p><p><strong>Should your client absolutely refuse to change the style or the fabric </strong>(for example, that lace fabric she chose herself), you will have to sew the entire top from super-elastic mesh fabric and then cover it with appliqué cut from the lace of her dream.</p><p><strong>We still need to take some classic sleeve measurements. </strong></p><p><strong>Upper Arm Circumference: </strong></p><p><strong>This measurement is taken a little below the armscye. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%207.files/image026.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>Elbow Circumference: </strong></p><p><strong>This measurement shows how much the sleeve should be able to stretch in the elbow area when your client bends her elbow. </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%207.files/image028.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>Sleeve Length: </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%207.files/image030.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>And, naturally, Wrist Circumference: </strong></p><p><strong>I would like to draw your attention to a seemingly insignificant moment which often gets neglected by inexperienced dressmakers when they measure Wrist Circumference. </strong></p><p><strong>A young slender girl will normally have a Wrist Circumference of about 14cm. </strong>And now go and try to put your hand in a sleeve with a circumference of 14cm, especially if it has a folded edge or is finished with scallop-edged lace trimming or bias tape! It will never fit into a narrow sleeve like that!</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%207.files/image032.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>For this reason, instead of measuring the actual Wrist Circumference, I measure the circumference of my client’s hand with her fingers pressed together like in the picture below. </strong>You can be sure that her hand will fit in the sleeve if you do it this way! You must never forget this small detail!</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%207.files/image034.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>Of course, the sleeve will be a little looser then, but only in this case will your client’s hand fit in! </strong>If she insists on keeping the sleeves narrow in the wrist, then you should discuss possible technical solutions. You can, for example, make a slit in the sleeve and add a regular button, a snap button, a bow or a hook-and-eye closure so she can unfasten it, put her hand through, and then fasten it again to make it narrow.</p><p><strong>I have basically named all supplementary measurements required for the front of a corset garment with shoulder parts. </strong>They are similar to measurements taken for classic garments, but you should always remember that a corset garment is a hard construction which hugs the wearer’s curves tightly.</p><p><strong>It is time to take measurement for the back of our garment. </strong></p><p><strong>Shoulder to Shoulder Across Back: </strong></p><p><strong>It is a very important measurement which indicates the degree of stoop of your client’s back. </strong></p><p><strong>A healthy posture implies that a person’s shoulder width should be about 10-15mm bigger across the back than across the front. That is for a regular healthy body. </strong></p><p><strong>But there are women with a hollow back or sway back posture. </strong>It is simply more comfortable for them to stand that way. And their shoulder width across the back will be smaller than across the front.</p><p><strong>And, finally, there is a very commonly found case − a slouched posture where shoulder width is considerably bigger across the back than across the front. </strong></p><p><strong>Comparing Shoulder to Shoulder Across Front with Shoulder to Shoulder Across Back will help you a lot in the making and customizing of your pattern. </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%207.files/image036.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>Nape to Waist: </strong></p><p>This measurement allows you to define the back neckline curve so you can rely on it when adjusting the pattern to client’s measurements.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%207.files/image038.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>Shoulder Slope Back: </strong></p><p><strong>This measurement is the distance from centre waist point (where the spine intersects with the waistline) and the tip of the shoulder where the arm begins. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%207.files/image040.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>Full Length Back: </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%207.files/image042.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>Please note </strong>that if you want to slightly lower the armscye, then all these shoulder-related lengths need to be measured down to the new lowered armscye point, both for the front and for the back.</p><p><strong>Full Length Back and Shoulder Slope Back indicate the shoulder slant for the back of your pattern. </strong></p><p><strong>Slim-fit garments often have a different shoulder slant at the front and at the back. </strong></p><p>Shoulders are usually straighter from the back. Do not be concerned by this! When you assemble the garment, everything will fall into place. It will spread out properly when your client puts it on. I always add a couple of centimeters to the seam allowance of the shoulder seam just to be on the safe side: it allows me to play around with the balance between the front and the back and with the position of the side seam.</p><p><strong>Relying on my experience, I would also like to say </strong>that chances are high you will create a perfect fit from the first time with correctly taken measurements. And that is possible if your client follows your directions during the taking of measurements, does not toss and turn and change her pose all the time, and if you, in your turn, do your job quickly and accurately not letting your client get tired.</p><p><strong>Width Back: </strong></p><p>You have probably already taken this measurement because it is compulsory if your garment has extended corners at the back for attaching shoulder straps.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%207.files/image044.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>In conclusion, let us talk about shoulder straps. </strong></p><p><strong>We will talk about shoulder straps cut one piece with the garment a little later. </strong>They are sewn after certain patterns which are also included in this book.</p><p><strong>And now I want to talk about shoulder straps which are cut separately and sewn to the corset. </strong></p><p>There are many ways shoulder straps can be positioned depending on the style of the garment. They can be off-shoulder straps going along the edge of the shoulder, they can crisscross at the back, or they can be halter-neck straps, etc.</p><p><strong>None of these straps require any additional measurements </strong>apart from maybe off-shoulder straps: you may roughly measure Shoulder Strap Length to make a mock-up strap and pin it in place during a fitting.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%207.files/image046.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>As for the joining technique, I highly recommend you simply sew such straps to the inside of a fully finished garment </strong>and not try to secure them between the lining and the face. You can always finish the joint neatly with thin lace or bias tape.</p><p><strong>Putting shoulder straps in-between the lining and the face is a thankless job. It takes a lot of time and effort and there is no guarantee that the results will make you happy. </strong>There are lots of contributing factors, such as, for example, lack of symmetry in your client’s figure. There have been cases in my practice where the left shoulder strap was shorter than the right one by as much as 2cm because the client had different shoulders. So even if one sewn-in strap sits well, the other one will inevitably start to slide off the shoulder or go askew despite being an exact copy of the first one and sewn in at the same level.</p><p><strong>I have completely given up the method of putting shoulder straps in-between the face and the lining. I prefer sewing them to the inside of the garment when it is finished and then finishing the joint neatly. </strong>Besides, I must say that straps sewn to the inside hold a lot better than straps secured in-between the face and the lining. The joining seam may easily rip under a little tension!</p><p><strong>In other words, I highly recommend you should attach shoulder straps to an already finished garment put on your client. </strong>Your final task is to put them in the right place, secure them with pins, sew them to the inside of the garment, and do a clean finish on the joint.</p></div> <!-- Itemprop END: articleBody --></div> <!-- Scope END: Article --><!-- END Schema.org microdata added by the Add-Meta-Tags WordPress plugin --> 					</div>															<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane" id="pattern">						<p>Sewing patterns are in PDF format.</p><p>To print sewing patterns open the files, press “print” and choose “<strong>PRINT IN ACTUAL SIZE</strong>“.</p><p>In each&nbsp;file the pattern is divided &nbsp;to A4 paper sheets for home printer.</p><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/patterns/4%20curves%20corset%20-%20boat.pdf" target="_blank" class=""><img src="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset-rs/img/pdf.png"> Boat-Neck Corset with 4 Princess Seams</a><br><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/pattern